<doc id="638965" wikidata="Q5288825" url="?curid=638965" title="Dolabella (gastropod)">
<text>Dolabella is a genus of sea slugs or sea hares, marine opisthobranch gastropod mollusks in the family Aplysiidae, the sea hares.

==Description==
In the sea hares of the genus &quot;Dolabella&quot; the back end of the body has turned into a slanted disc-like shield, with a large, calcified shell buried inside. The color is variable, with specks of green and brown.

There are fossil records of † &quot;Dolabella aldrichi&quot; from the Early Miocene, found in the Chipola Formation in Florida 

==Species==
Species within the genus &quot;Dolabella&quot; include:
* † &quot;Dolabella aldrichi&quot;
* &quot;Dolabella auricularia&quot; or Wedge Sea Hare
* &quot;Dolabella gigas&quot; 
**Distribution : Indian Ocean.
**Description : The internal shell has a saucer-shaped extension; armed penis
;Species brought into synonymy:
* &quot;Dolabella aldrichi&quot; †: synonym of &quot;Floribella aldrichi&quot; † (original combination)
* &quot;Dolabella andersoni&quot; : synonym of &quot;Dolabella auricularia&quot; 
* &quot;Dolabella callosa&quot; : synonym of &quot;Dolabella auricularia&quot; 
* &quot;Dolabella cheni&quot; : synonym of &quot;Dolabella auricularia&quot; 
* &quot;Dolabella dolabrifera&quot; : synonym of &quot;Dolabrifera dolabrifera&quot; 
* &quot;Dolabella ecaudata&quot; : synonym of &quot;Dolabella auricularia&quot; 
* &quot;Dolabella fragilis&quot; : synonym of &quot;Aplysia depilans&quot; 
* &quot;Dolabella gigas&quot; : synonym of &quot;Dolabella auricularia&quot; 
* &quot;Dolabella hasselti&quot; : synonym of &quot;Dolabella auricularia&quot; 
* &quot;Dolabella laevis&quot; : synonym of &quot;Aplysia depilans&quot; 
* &quot;Dolabella lepus&quot; : synonym of &quot;Aplysia depilans&quot; (dubious synonym)
* &quot;Dolabella rumphii&quot; : synonym of &quot;Dolabella auricularia&quot; 
* &quot;Dolabella scapula&quot; : synonym of &quot;Dolabella auricularia&quot; (non-binomial)
* &quot;Dolabella variegata&quot; : synonym of &quot;Dolabella auricularia&quot; 

